Determine Variant Caller Consensus

C. Savonen for ALSF CCDL

2019

Purpose: After running the initial analyses of each variant caller, this notebook combines the output from those calculations, compares them, and outputs the consensus for the mutation callers.

Summary of Findings:

Due to some of the findings here, I suggest we should move forward with mutations called by Strelka2, Mutect2, and Lancet. And, due to its oversensitivity that VarDicts data can be dropped entirely.

Individual Callers Reports

  • Lancet
  • MuTect2
  • Strelka2
  • Vardict

Notable Findings:

  • VarDict calls more mutations than any of the other callers. Many of these have very low suggesting that some may be sequencing errors.

  • Mutect2, Strelka2, and Lancet do have plenty of mutations in common.

Outline of analyses completed:

  • Upset graph
  • VAF of combinations of callers
  • Base changes by caller
  • VAF distributions by caller
  • TMB distributions by caller
  • VAF correlations between callers
  • TMB correlations between callers

Usage

To run this from the command line, use:

Rscript -e "rmarkdown::render('analyses/snv-callers/consensus_snv_callers.Rmd', 
                              clean = TRUE)"

This assumes you are in the top directory of the repository.

Set up a function for calculating the percent off mutations of a caller for a given variable.

perc_mutation_by_caller <- function(df, var) {
  # Summarizes a variable and calculates the percent of mutations for a caller
  # for each category
  #
  # Args:
  #   df: a data.frame with `caller` as a column.
  #   var: a string identifying the column of the variable you need to summarize by.
  #
  # Returns:
  #   a data.frame with a summarized percent of caller mutations calculated in
  #   the `percent` column.

  # Summarize by the number of times each category shows up
  count_df <- df %>%
    dplyr::group_by(caller, eval(parse(text = var))) %>%
    dplyr::summarise(count = dplyr::n())

  # Calculate sum totals for each caller
  totals <- count_df %>%
    dplyr::group_by(caller) %>%
    dplyr::summarise(total = sum(count, na.rm = TRUE))

  # Calculate percentages based on totals
  count_df <- count_df %>%
    as.data.frame() %>%
    dplyr::mutate("percent" = count_df$count / totals$total[match(
      count_df$caller,
      totals$caller
    )])

  # Rename the column as what it was before
  colnames(count_df)[2] <- var

  # Return this data.frame
  return(count_df)
}
